@DATABASE "Wheel of Fortune, v6.41 File Format Guide"
@Node Main "Welcome to Wheel of Fortune, v6.41's Programmers Guide!"
-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-
   Wheel of Fortune, @{"v6.41" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/HISTORY.GUIDE/V641"} Programmers Guide by @{"Dotoran" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/REGISTER.GUIDE/DOTORAN"} of @{"Frontiers" link "pfiles:WoFortune/Guides/REGISTER.GUIDE/FRONTIERS"}!!
-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-
                View the format for which support file:

   @{" WoFortune.Config " link CONFIG} : Contains default game variable values.
   @{" _WOF             " link UCONFIG} : Contains user's config variables.
   @{" GameData         " link GAMEDATA} : Contains info on the current game.
   @{" Players          " link PLAYERS} : Contains info for all game players.
   @{" PuzData          " link PUZDATA} : Contains encrypted puzzle data.
   @{" LastPlayer       " link LASTPLAYER} : Contains info on the last player.
   @{" LastReset        " link LASTRESET} : Contains info on the last game reset.
   @{" Stats            " link STATS} : Contains hall of fame data.
   @{" Winner           " link WINNER} : Contains info on winner of last regular game.
   @{" BWinner          " link BWINNER} : Contains info on winner of last bonus game.
   @{" Winners          " link WINNERS} : Contains info on winners of previous regular games.
   @{" BWinners         " link BWINNERS} : Contains info on winners of previous bonus games.
   @{" Millionaires     " link MILLIONAIRES} : Contains regular game play millionaires.
   @{" BMillionaires    " link BMILLIONAIRES} : Contains regular bonus play millionaires.
   @{" Bankers          " link BANKERS} : Contains master game player listings.
@endnode
@Node PUZDATA "The PuzData File"

 PuzData
~~~~~~~~~
Info: A Relative file containing 351 records(unregistered version), and
      2000+ records(registered versions).

      1st record is 5 characters long, padded in Ascii 0's. This holds
      the TOTAL number of Puzzles to follow.

      Remaining records hold Puzzle data. Each record is 90 characters
      long, containing 3 fields, each padded in Ascii 0's:

            Puzzle is 50 characters
            Clue   is 20 characters
            Author is 20 characters

      All item data is coded using the "!" to "~" reverse Ascii code
      order.
@endnode
@Node GAMEDATA "The GameData File"

 GameData
~~~~~~~~~~
Info: Main "Current Game" support file, which is stored in the specified
      Wheel of Fortune config path(as defined in the CONFIG file).

      This file contains seven(7) data lines, as defined below:

1: Current Puzzle Number

2: Solved Portion of Puzzle (Using "!" to "~" Coding) (@ UnSolved)
                                                      (_ Coded)

3: Current Puzzle Answer    (Using "!" to "~" Coding)

4: Letters Already Guessed  (Using NO MCI Codes)

5: Current Puzzle Clue      (Using "!" to "~" Coding)

6: Puzzle Author, Number of Next Puzzle & Bonus Puzzle to Use:

    v1|v2|v3|j
    |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
    |  |  `-----> next bonus puzzle number to start with.
    |  `--------> next regular game puzzle to slect.
    `-----------> author of current puzzle.

7: Number of Consonants & Vowels Left to Solve:

    v1|v2|j
    |  |  `--> junk filler character.
    |  `-----> number of vowels in current puzzle.
    `--------> number of consonants in current puzzle.
@endnode
@Node PLAYERS "The Players File"

 Players
~~~~~~~~~
Info: This file contains data for all players that have ever played a
      game of Wheel of Fortune, whether present or past. Each player
      is given one data line, formatted as follows:

    v1|v2|v3|v4|v5|v6|v7|v8|v9|v10|v11|j

 v1: handle of this player.
 v2: total number of puzzles ever won by this player.
 v3: total amount of money ever won by this player.
 v4: current puzzle number this player is involved with.
 v5: amount of money this player currently has to play with.
 v6: total number of times this player has played the game.
 v7: winning percentile for this player(games won / total games played)
 v8: total number of bonus games this player has ever won.
 v9: total amount of bonus money this player has won.
v10: total number of millions player has won in regular games.
v11: total number of millions player has won in bonus games.
  j: junk fill character
@endnode
@Node STATS "The Stats File"

 Stats
~~~~~~~
Info: This file contains six(6) data lines, which are used to store the
      hall of fame scores. Each line contains a Handle, Value, and junk
      filler character. The lines are defined as:

1: Who played the most number of times in regular rounds.
2: Who won the most puzzles in the regular rounds.
3: Who won the most money in regular round play.
4: Who won the most money in one game of regular play.
5: Who won the most puzzles in the bonus round.
6: Who won the most money in bonus round play.
@endnode
@Node WINNER "The Winner File"

 Winner
~~~~~~~~
Info: This file contains one line used to store information on the
      winner of the last regular game. The line contains five(5) data
      items, plus a junk filler as defined below:

    v1|v2|v3|v4|v5|j
    |  |  |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
    |  |  |  |  `-----> the total number of wins this player currently has.
    |  |  |  `--------> the amount of money they earned for guessing it.
    |  |  `-----------> the date(YYYYMMDD format) puzzle was guessed on.
    |  `--------------> the puzzle that this player guessed correctly.
    `-----------------> handle of player who won last regular game.
@endnode
@Node BWINNER "The BWinner File"

 BWinner
~~~~~~~~~
Info: This file contains one line used to store information on the
      winner of the last bonus game. The line contains five(5) data
      items, plus a junk filler as defined below:

    v1|v2|v3|v4|v5|j
    |  |  |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
    |  |  |  |  `-----> the total number of wins this player currently has.
    |  |  |  `--------> the amount of money they earned for guessing it.
    |  |  `-----------> the date(YYYYMMDD format) puzzle was guessed on.
    |  `--------------> the puzzle that this player guessed correctly.
    `-----------------> handle of player who won last bonus game.
@endnode
@Node WINNERS "The Winners File"

 Winners
~~~~~~~~~
Info: This file contains a listing of past regular round winners. How
      many entries this file has is SysOp configurable in the CONFIG
      file. The default value is 20. Each line is formatted as follows:

    v1|v2|v3|j
    |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
    |  |  `-----> the date(YYYYMMDD format) they guessed it on.
    |  `--------> the puzzle they guessed to win.
    `-----------> handle of player who won the game.
@endnode
@Node BWINNERS "The BWinners File"

 BWinners
~~~~~~~~~~
Info: This file contains a listing of past bonus round winners. How many
      entries this file has is SysOp configurable in the CONFIG file.
      The default value is 20. Each line is formatted as follows:

    v1|v2|v3|v4|j
    |  |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
    |  |  |  `-----> amount of bonus money player has won.
    |  |  `--------> the date(YYYYMMDD format) they guessed it on.
    |  `-----------> the puzzle they guessed to win.
    `--------------> handle of player who won the game.
@endnode
@Node LASTPLAYER "The LastPlayer File"

 LastPlayer
~~~~~~~~~~~~
Info: This file contains numerous pieces of personal info on the last
      player of the game(the one who last SPUN or BOUGHT a VOWEL).

      This file will only exist if there WAS a last player, so may NOT
      always be present in your WOF config path.

      Only the serial id number and handle is used with "simple" last
      player checking, while "complex" checking utilizes ALL the info.

      The one(1) data line used is formatted as follows:

    v1|v2|v3|v4|v5|v6|v7|j
    |  |  |  |  |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
    |  |  |  |  |  |  `-----> the hour number last player played game.
    |  |  |  |  |  `--------> the day number last player played game.
    |  |  |  |  `-----------> the data phone number of the last player.
    |  |  |  `--------------> the voice phone number of the last player.
    |  |  `-----------------> the street address of the last player.
    |  `--------------------> the handle of the last player.
    `-----------------------> the serial id number of the last player.
@endnode
@Node MILLIONAIRES "The Millionaires File"

 Millionaires
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Info: This file lists the players who have earned more than one million
      dollars in regular round playing. How many are saved in this list
      is SysOp definable in the CONFIG program. The default is 15. Each
      line is one millionaire's data, as defined below:

    v1|v2|v3|j
    |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
    |  |  `-----> handle of user who made the million dollars.
    |  `--------> date(YYYMMDD format) they made their last million.
    `-----------> how many millions this player earned.
@endnode
@Node BMILLIONAIRES "The BMillionaires File"

 BMillionaires
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Info: This file lists the players who have earned more than one million
      dollars in bonus round playing. How many are saved in this list
      is SysOp definable in the CONFIG program. The default is 15. Each
      line is one millionaire's data, as defined below:

    v1|v2|v3|j
    |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
    |  |  `-----> handle of user who made the million dollars.
    |  `--------> date(YYYMMDD format) they made their last million.
    `-----------> how many millions this player earned.
@endnode
@Node BANKERS "The Bankers File"

 Bankers
~~~~~~~~~
Info: This file lists players who have earned the title of Banker. How
      many millions a player needs in order to become a banker, as well
      as how many entries this listing can hold are both configurable by
      the SysOp through the CONFIG program. Each line holds one banker's
      data, as defined below:

    v1|v2|v3|v4|j
    |  |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
    |  |  |  `-----> how this player became a banker. 1 of 4 values:
    |  |  |          0=neither, 1=regular, 2=bonus, 3=both rounds.
    |  |  `--------> handle of user who earned these millions.
    |  `-----------> date(YYYYMMDD format) they earned these millions.
    `--------------> how many millions this player has earned.
@endnode
@Node LASTRESET "The LastReset File"

 LastReset
~~~~~~~~~~~
Info: This file contains two date lines holding information as to the
      last time the game was reset. The lines are formatted as:

1: Date(YYYYMMDD format) of last game reset.
2: Handle of last master of the game. This will be "No One Yet!" at
   first, and may be "Time Expired!" if the SysOp chooses to reset the
   game after a specified period of time.
@endnode
@Node UCONFIG "The _WOF User Config File"

 _WOF
~~~~~~
Info: This file is unique to each wheel of fortune player, meaning that
      each player has their own file. The file is stored in the user's
      UUCP mail directory(like "mail:users/1/" etc.). The file holds the
      data for the user's current user config values, as well as housing
      the data which makes up their "prize history" listing.

      The first line holds the user config data, and is formatted:

    v1|v2|v3|v4|v5|v6|v7|v8|v9|v10|v11|v12|v13|v14|j

 v1: Send "I Won!" broadcast olm messages.
     (0=No, 1=Yes, 2=Ask Player)
 v2: Show regular millionaires listing.
     (0=No, 1=Yes, 2=Ask Player)
 v3: Show bonus millionaires listing.
     (0=No, 1=Yes, 2=Ask Player)
 v4: Show all time best(banker) wof player listing.
     (0=No, 1=Yes, 2=Ask Player)
 v5: Show the graphic vanna picture.
     (0=No, 1=Yes, 2=Ask Player) [Age of player first considered]
 v6: Show old(previous) game play log.
     (0=No, 1=Yes, 2=Ask Player)
 v7: Show new(current) game play log.
     (0=No, 1=Yes, 2=Ask Player)
 v8: Which type of wheel graphic for ASC.
     (0=Wedges, 1=Quick, 3=Ask Player)
 v9: Which type of wheel graphic for ANS.
     (0=Wedges, 1=Quick, 2=Spinning, 3=Ask Player)
v10: Which type of wheel graphic for IBM.
     (0=Wedges, 1=Quick, 2=Spinning, 3=Ask Player)
v11: Guess formatting for ASCII module.
     (0=Regular, 2=Fill-In-Knowns, 4=Ask Player)
v12: Guess formatting for ANSI module.
     (0=Regular, 1=Reg-Timer, 2=Fill-In-Knowns, 3=Fill-In-Holes
      4=Ask Player)
v13: Guess formatting for IBM-ANSI module.
     (0=Regular, 1=Reg-Timer, 2=Fill-In-Knowns, 3=Fill-In-Holes,
      4=Ask Player)
v14: Quit or restart game on bad guesses.
     (0=Quit, 1=Restart, 2=Ask Player)
  j: junk filler character.

      Any additional lines present in the file hold data concerning the
      player's prize history. How many prizes to contain in this file is
      definable in the CONFIG file. Each line is formatted as follows:

    v1|v2|v3|v4|v5|v6|v7|j
    |  |  |  |  |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
    |  |  |  |  |  |  `-----> bonus graphic number given.
    |  |  |  |  |  `--------> amount of smart bonus money awarded.
    |  |  |  |  `-----------> did player use the smart bonus.
    |  |  |  `--------------> how much of the sysop award was given.
    |  |  `-----------------> which sysop bonus award was given.
    |  `--------------------> amount of initial bonus prize money.
    `-----------------------> date(YYYYMMDD format) prize was given.
@endnode
@Node CONFIG "The Wheel of Fortune Master Config File"

 WoFortune.Config
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
Info: This file is the main config file for the whole game, and is always
      to be found in the pfiles: assign'ed path. There are 13 different
      lines of data in this file, as formatted below:

      The first two lines are comment lines, however the data in line 1
      also serves to hold the version number and creation date all game
      files use for display purposes. They look like this:

 1: ; v6.41 August 6, 1995
 2: ;                        WOF CONFIG FILE, Supports ALL THREE Modules!

      The third line holds the designated game storage path, which will
      look like this as the default value:

 3: pfiles:WoFortune/

      The fourth line lists data concerning how the game loader should
      operate. Currently, there are 6 data items, plus 1 junk filler at
      the end of this line. It's format looks like this:

 4:  v1|v2|v3|v4|v5|v6|j
     |  |  |  |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
     |  |  |  |  |  `-----> game quick command. (WOF by default)
     |  |  |  |  `--------> ask player to load default game.
     |  |  |  `-----------> highest port number loaded.
     |  |  `--------------> lowest port number loaded.
     |  `-----------------> loader display mode, as defined below:
     |                      1=last game,2=current game,3=bonus game
     |                      4=last/current,5=last/bonus,6=current/bonus
     |                      7=last/current/bonus
     `--------------------> game closed? (0=No,1=Yes)

      The fifth line holds data concerning the hosts of the game:

 5:  v1|v2|v3|j
     |  |  |  `--> junk filler character.
     |  |  `-----> name of the female host.
     |  `--------> name of the male host.
     `-----------> names of both hosts(combined with " & ")

      Lines 6 thru 11 hold the data needed to create the "press any key"
      prompts in each module. [6-7(Ascii), 8-9(Ansi), and 10-11(IBM)].

 6:
 8:
10:  v1|v2|j
     |  |  `--> junk filler character.
     |  `-----> general use prompt(The "Pat Is Waiting" prompt)
     `--------> number of mci commands used to create this key.

 7:
 9:
11:  v1|v2|j
     |  |  `--> junk filler character.
     |  `-----> special use prompt(The "Vanna Wants You..." prompt)
     `--------> number of mci commands used to create this key.

      The twelth line holds data pertaining to the game of a general
      nature, meaning it could be of use by multiple modules. It is
      presently made up of 28 data items, plus 1 junk terminator, and
      is formatted this way:

12:  v1|v2|v3|v4|v5|v6|v7|v8|v9|v10|v11|v12|v13|v14|v15|v16|v17|v18| --.
                                                                       |
     .--------This-line-continued-(resides-on-ONE-line-internally)-----'
     |
     `-- v19|v20|v21|v22|v23|v24|v25|v26|v27|v28|j

 v1: reset game mode.
        (0=Never,1=Monthly,2=RegMils,3=BonMils,4=AnyMils,5=Banker)
 v2: reset game value.
        (Defaults: 0=N/A, 1=3, 2=10, 3=10, 4=20, 5=N/A)
 v3: sysop override for bad guess format.
        (0=Exit Game(Always),1=Restart Game(Always),2=Ask(UserConfig))
 v4: can winner of current game be first player of next game?
        (0=No,1=Yes(User is ASKED if they wish to play again))
 v5: last player checking format.
        (0=Simple,1=Complex)[Possible hourly wait period also]
 v6: character to use for unsolved letters in current puzzle, when
        using the ASCII module. (defaults to using "+"(plus)).
 v7: character to use for unsolved letters in current puzzle, when
        using the ANSI module. (defaults to using "@"(at symbol)).
 v8: character to use for unsolved letters in current puzzle, when
        using the IBM-ANSI module. (defaults to using "@"(at symbol)).
 v9: can players with no current winnings attempt to guess puzzle?
        (0=No,1=Yes)
v10: maximum number of winners to store in the "Winners" file.
        (defaults to "10")
v11: display the graphic vanna white picture?
        (0=No(Always),1=Yes,2=14yr,3=16yr(1,2,3 all user configurable))
v12: which users have access to use the maint/main config file?
        (1=ID #1, 2=Group23, 3=Group31, 4=System Operator Priviledge)
v13: maximum number of players to store in the "Bankers" file.
        (defaults to "15")
v14: maximum number of players to store in the "Millionaires" file.
        (defaults to "15")
v15: maximum number of players to store in the "BMillionaires" file.
        (defaults to "15")
v16: number of millions a player needs to earn to become next Banker.
        (defaults to "10")
v17: user play again chance.
        (0=No, 1=Yes(1:10 chance), 2=6hr, 3=12hr, 4=18hr, 5=24hr)
v18: can new users and/or guests play the game?
        (0=No,1=Yes)
v19: spinning wheel "click" speed(in 1/50th of seconds)
        (defaults to "5")
v20: can player use previous funds in current turn?
        (0=No,1=Yes)
v21: should broadcast olm's be sent at start(and upon winning)?
        (0=No(Always), 1=Yes(Always), 2=Ask(user configurable))
v22: should the letter Y be used as a vowel?
        (0=No, 1=Yes)
v23: first custom surprise type.
        (defaults to "Time")
v24: first custom surprise value.
        (defaults to "10" [minutes])
v25: second custom surprise type.
        (defaults to "None")
v26: second custom surprise value.
        (defaults to "N/A")
v27: third custom surprise type.
        (defaults to "None")
v28: third custom surprise value.
        (defaults to "N/A")
  j: junk filler character.

      The thirteenth(and last) line of data concerns the Bonus Round. It
      contains 18 items, plus one filler, and is formatted like this:

    v1|v2|v3|v4|v5|v6|v7|v8|v9|v10|v11|v12|v13|v14|v15|v16|v17|v18|j

 v1: amount of time(in seconds) to allow guessing of bonus puzzle.
        (defaults to "30" [seconds])
 v2: maximum number of players to store in the "BWinners" file.
        (defaults to "10")
 v3: minimum length a puzzle must be to be used in bonus round.
        (defaults to "20")
 v4: should the smart bonus letters be used?
        (0=No, 1=Yes, 2=Ask)
 v5: show bonus puzzle at round's end?
        (1=Never, 2=If Out of Time, 3=If Guessed Wrong, 4=Always)
 v6: amount of money to award as the smart bonus prize.
        (defaults to "1500" [$1,500.00])
 v7: First SysOp (BBS) prize to award regular winners.
        (0=None, 1=Time, 2=GameP, 3=ByteC, 4=FileC)
 v8: First SysOp (BBS) prize amount to award regular winners.
        (Defaults: 0=N/A, 1=10, 2=1000, 3=10000, 4=3)
 v9: Second SysOp (BBS) prize to award regular winners.
        (0=None, 1=Time, 2=GameP, 3=ByteC, 4=FileC)
v10: Second SysOp (BBS) prize amount to award regular winners.
        (Defaults: 0=N/A, 1=10, 2=1000, 3=10000, 4=3)
v11: Third SysOp (BBS) prize to award regular winners.
        (0=None, 1=Time, 2=GameP, 3=ByteC, 4=FileC)
v12: Third SysOp (BBS) prize amount to award regular winners.
        (Defaults: 0=N/A, 1=10, 2=1000, 3=10000, 4=3)
v13: First SysOp (BBS) prize to award bonus round winners.
        (0=None, 1=Time, 2=GameP, 3=ByteC, 4=FileC)
v14: First SysOp (BBS) prize amount to award bonus round winners.
        (Defaults: 0=N/A, 1=10, 2=1000, 3=10000, 4=3)
v15: Second SysOp (BBS) prize to award bonus round winners.
        (0=None, 1=Time, 2=GameP, 3=ByteC, 4=FileC)
v16: Second SysOp (BBS) prize amount to award bonus round winners.
        (Defaults: 0=N/A, 1=10, 2=1000, 3=10000, 4=3)
v17: Third SysOp (BBS) prize to award bonus round winners.
        (0=None, 1=Time, 2=GameP, 3=ByteC, 4=FileC)
v18: Third SysOp (BBS) prize amount to award bonus round winners.
        (Defaults: 0=N/A, 1=10, 2=1000, 3=10000, 4=3)
  j: junk filler character.
@endnode
